@node "Weeks" "How the ancient Jews used the term `weeks'"
@{b}@{u}How the ancient Jews used the term `weeks'@{ub}@{uu}

The ancient Jews commonly thought in terms of weeks of years.

For instance, just as every seventh day was a Sabbath day, every seventh
year, was a Sabbath year. - Exodus 20:8-11;  23:10, 11.
@endnode

@node "Shiloh"
@{b}@{u}Shiloh@{ub}@{uu}

The name Shiloh means "He Whose It Is;  He to Whom It Belongs."  In time,
it became evident that "Shiloh" was Jesus Christ, "the Lion that is of the
tribe of Judah."  (Revelation 5:5)  Some of the Jewish Targums simply
replaced the word "Shiloh" with "the Messiah" or "the king Messiah."
@endnode

@node "World" "System of Things"
@{b}@{u}System of Things@{ub}@{uu}

Some Bibles use the word "world" instead of "system of things."
W. E. Vine's @{i}Expository Dictionary of New Testament Words@{ui} says that
the Greek word @{i}ai-on'@{ui} "signifies a period of indefinite duration,
or time viewed in relation to what takes place un the period."
Parkhurst's @{i}Greek and English Lexicon to the New Testament@{ui} (page 17)
includes the expression "this system of things" in discussing the
use of @{i}ai-o'nes@{ui} (plural) at Hebrews 1:2.  So the rendering
"system of things" is in harmony with the original Greek text.
@endnode

@node "Divorce"
@{b}@{u}Divorce@{ub}@{uu}

The only Scriptural ground for divorce allowing for remarriage is
"fornicaton" - sex relations outside the marriage. - Matthew 19:9
@endnode

